@deffn Syntax let/with-class ((@ameta{var} @ameta{init}) ...) @ameta{body}
Like @func{let} but automatically enclose the body in a
@func{with-fields} syntax using the specified class types.  Each
@meta{var} element can be one among:

@example
@ameta{id}
(@ameta{id} @ametao{class name} @ameta{class name} ...)
@end example

@noindent
in which: @meta{id} must be an identifier representing the variable
name, @ameta{class name} must be an identifier representing a class
name.

If all the @meta{var} arguments are in the first form (untyped
variable): @func{let/with-class} defaults to @func{let} as defined by
@rnrs{6}.  If at least one @meta{var} has type: the untyped ones default
to bindings with @class{top} as conventional class type name.

@example
(define-class <fraction>
  (fields (mutable number))
  (virtual-fields (immutable numerator)
                  (immutable denominator)))

(define (<fraction>-numerator o)
  (numerator (<fraction>-number o)))

(define (<fraction>-denominator o)
  (denominator (<fraction>-number o)))

(let/with-class (((a <fraction>) (make-<fraction> 2/3))
                 ((b <fraction>) (make-<fraction> 4/5)))
  (list a.numerator b.denominator))
