@defunx make-c-callout/with-errno @var{ret-type} @var{address} @var{arg-types}
Build and return a new Scheme callout closure for a C language foreign
function whose address is specified by the @var{address} pointer
object.

@var{ret-type} must be a symbol in the @code{clang-external-types}
enumeration; it represents the type of the foreign function return
value.  @var{arg-types} must be a list of symbols in the
@code{clang-external-types} enumeration; they represent the types of the
foreign function arguments.

The @samp{/with-errno} variant returns a callout closure which, when
evaluated, returns two values: the return value from the foreign
function and the value of the C standard variable @code{errno} right
after the foreign function call.

@quotation
@strong{NOTE} Some @posix{} functions return an integer representing
success or failure and only when the returned value represents failure
the @samp{errno} value is meaningful.
@end quotation

The returned closure:

@enumerate
@item
Accepts as many Scheme object arguments as there are symbols in
@var{arg-types}; to specify an empty list of arguments, we can use
@code{(void)}.

@item
Does marshaling from Scheme arguments to C language values as specified
by the @var{arg-types} symbols.

@item
Applies the foreign function to the C values.

@item
Returns the return value of the foreign function, marshaled to a Scheme
value as specified by the @var{ret-type} symbol.
@end enumerate
@end defun


@defun make-c-function @var{shared-object} @var{ret-type} @var{funcname} @var{arg-types}
@defunx make-c-function/with-errno @var{shared-object} @var{ret-type} @var{funcname} @var{arg-types}
Wrappers for the @func{make-c-callout} functions which determine the
address of the function by looking for the @var{funcname} symbol in the
@var{shared-object} using @func{lookup-shared-object*}.

Beware that, sometimes, the exported symbols are different from the ones
we write in C language code to call a function.  If the foreign symbol
is not found, a continuable exception is raised with
@func{raise-shared-object-lookup-error}; returning to the continuation
must return the address of the function.  @ref{ffi core conditions
lookup, Shared objects lookup error}.

@quotation
@strong{For Unix} One way to discover the names of symbols exported by a
shared object, is to apply the @command{strings} command to the shared
object itself.  For example, to discover the names of deflate functions
in Zlib:

@example
$ strings /usr/lib/libz.so | grep deflate
deflateInit_
deflate
deflateEnd
...
@end example
@end quotation
@end defun

