@subsubsection Calling Scheme functions


The following bindings are exported by the @library{ffi primitives}
library and reexported by the @library{ffi} compound library.  As
example, the following form defines a callback accepting three
@samp{int} as arguments and returning an @samp{int}:

@example
(define (fn a b c)
  (* a b c))

(define cb
  (make-c-callback 'int fn '(int int int)))
@end example


@defun make-c-callback @var{ret-type} @var{scheme-proc} @var{arg-types}
Build and return a callback object to be used as argument to a callout
procedure.  The callback invokes the Scheme function @var{scheme-proc}.

@var{ret-type} must be a symbol in the @code{clang-external-types}
enumeration; it represents the type of the callback return value.
@var{arg-types} must be a list of symbols in the
@code{clang-external-types} enumeration; they represent the types of the
callback arguments.

When a foreign function invokes the C language callback, the callback:

@enumerate
@item
Accepts as many C language arguments as there are symbols in
@var{arg-types}; to specify an empty list of arguments, we can use
@code{(void)}.

@item
Does marshaling from C language arguments to Scheme objects as specified
by the @var{arg-type} symbols.

@item
Applies the Scheme function to the Scheme values.

@item
Returns the return value of the Scheme function, marshaled to a C
language value as specified by the @var{ret-type} symbol.
@end enumerate

Every time a callback is built, a small amount of memory is allocated;
such memory cannot be subject to garbage collection, so it is leaked
unless we apply @func{free-c-callback} to the callback object.
@end defun


@defun free-c-callback @var{callback}
Release the memory associated to @var{callback}.  On some Scheme
implementations this call does nothing, because they do not allow
releasing such a resource.
@end defun

